No, both the classes are not thread safe.
You have to use synchronisation mechanism to achieve thread safety.

 1. You can use synchronized keyword in the parent class&#39;s getter and setter.
 2. Or you can use other synchronisation mechanism to achieve the thread safety like ReentrantLock or Semaphores.

Can you please elaborate more on this?

Just putting a sample code, to achieve thread safety using semaphores.

    import java.util.concurrent.Semaphore;

    public abstract class ParentClass {
      private String familyName;
      private final Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(1); // Initialize with one permit

      public String getFamily() {
        return familyName;
      }

      public void setFamily(String familyName) {
        try {
            semaphore.acquire(); // Acquire the permit
            this.familyName = familyName;
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        } finally {
            semaphore.release(); // Release the permit
        }
      }
     }

    public class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
      private String firstName;

      public String getFirstName() {
        return firstName;
      }

      public void setFirstName(String firstName) {
        this.firstName = firstName;
      }
    }

This ensures that only one thread can modify the familyName at a time, making it thread-safe.

    var child = new ChildClass()
    child.setFirstName(&quot;Jo&quot;);
    child.setFamilyName(&quot;Smith&quot;);

Technically, those lines are thread-safe because the object that `child` refers to is *thread confined*; i.e. it is only accessible from one thread.  

And if another thread *could* access the `child` instance, then the application as a whole would not be thread-safe.  (There are some complicated exceptions to this, but lets not go there.)

However, the classes themselves are NOT thread-safe.  The location of the methods in the superclass or subclass makes no difference to thread safety.  If you want those classes to be unconditionally thread-safe, then you need to add some explicit synchronization mechanism, OR rewrite them to be immutable classes.

-----------------------

Note that thread-safety is technically difficult to define in precise terms.  One approach is to start with some code that is functionally correct (per some specified requirements) when executed with only one thread.  If the code is *also* functionally correct for *all possible executions* involving more than one thread, then the code is thread safe.

So if we are going to ask the question is class `XYZ` thread safe, we first need a specification that `XYZ` needs to meet.  In your example classes, we can infer a specification that says that the getters return the values most recently set by the corresponding setters.  Your classes are NOT thread-safe per that specification because the lack of synchronization means that there can be memory anomalies.  But declaring the getters and setters as `synchronized` methods would be sufficient for thread-safety with respect to that spec.

